<chapter xml:id="chapter-opt" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Extreme values and optimization</title>

<section xml:id="section-opt-abs-extremes">
<title>Absolute extreme values</title>

<p>
An important question we often need to ask about a model is
<q>How high or low will this quantity go?</q>
Since our graph-sketching procedure from <xref ref="section-curves-shape" /> provides us with a relatively complete picture of the model's trends,
we can answer this question from such a sketch.
But often that is much more work than really necessary to answer the question,
so in this section we will develop a more efficient process based on local extremes.
</p>

<p> But first, we should be clear about what we are looking for. </p>

<definition xml:id="definition-opt-abs-extremes">
	<title>Absolute extremes</title>
	<p>
	<ul>

		<li>
			A function <m>q(t)</m> is said to have an <term>absolute minimum at <m>t = t^\ast</m></term>
			on a specific domain if <m>q(t^\ast) \le q(t)</m> for all other <m>t</m>-values in that domain.
			In this case, <m>q(t^\ast)</m> called the <term>absolute minimum value of <m>q</m></term> on that domain.
		</li>

		<li>
			A function <m>q(t)</m> is said to have an <term>absolute maximum at <m>t = t^\ast</m></term>
			on a specific domain if <m>q(t^\ast) \ge q(t)</m> for all other <m>t</m>-values in that domain.
			In this case, <m>q(t^\ast)</m> called the <term>absolute maximum value of <m>q</m></term> on that domain.
		</li>

	</ul>
	In general,
	we say that <m>q</m> has an <term>absolute extreme</term> at <m>t = t^\ast</m> if it has either a local minimum or a local maximum there.
	</p>

</definition>

<remark><p>
	Notice that both parts of the definition use an <em>or-equal-to</em> sign instead of a strict inequality.
	This is because it is possible for a function to achieve its absolute extreme values in multiple locations.
</p></remark>

<example xml:id="example-opt-changing-domains">
	<title>Changing the domain changes the absolute extremes</title>

	<p>
	If we consider <m>q(t) = t^2</m> on the domain <m>-1 \le t \le 2</m>,
	then the absolute minimum is <m>q(0) = 0</m> and the absolute maximum is <m>q(2) = 4</m>.
	However, if we consider <m>q(t) = t^2</m> on the domain <m>t \ge -1</m>,
	then the absolute minimum is the same but there is no longer any absolute maximum as <m>q \to \infty</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-opt-changing-domain">
		<caption>Existence of absolute extremes can depend on the domain.</caption>

		<sidebyside valign="middle" widths="41.7% 44.1%"> <!-- margins=""  -->

			<figure>
				<caption>A parabola on a restricted domain with both an absolute minimum and maximum.</caption>
				<image xml:id="image-opt-parabola-min-max-changing-domains-1">
					<description>Graph of a parabola on a restricted domain with both an absolute minimum and maximum.</description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="opt.d/parabola-min-max-changing-domains-1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>

			<figure>
				<caption>A parabola on a less restricted domain with an absolute minimum and but no absolute maximum.</caption>
				<image xml:id="image-opt-parabola-min-max-changing-domains-2">
					<description>Graph of a parabola on a less restricted domain with an absolute minimum but no absolute maximum.</description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="opt.d/parabola-min-max-changing-domains-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>

		</sidebyside>

	</figure>

</example>

<example>
	<title>A function with two absolute maximum locations</title>

	<p>
	For <m>\sin(t)</m> on the domain <m>0 \lt t \lt 3 \pi</m>,
	the absolute minimum value of <m>-1</m> occurs at only one location: <me> \sin(3 \pi / 2) = -1 </me>.
	However, the absolute maximum value of <m>1</m> occurs at two locations:
	<md><mrow> \sin(\pi / 2) \amp = 1 \amp \sin(5 \pi / 2) \amp = 1 </mrow></md>.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-opt-multiple-maxes">
		<caption>The sine graph can have multiple absolute extremes.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-opt-sin-mins-and-maxes" width="49.7%">
			<description>Demonstrating multiple absolute extremes on the sine graph.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="opt.d/sin-mins-and-maxes.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	If we expanded to the full domain for the sine function,
	there would still only be one absolute minimum <em>value</em> of <m>-1</m>
	and only one absolute maximum <em>value</em> of <m>1</m>,
	but the function achieves these values at an infinite number of <m>t</m>-values.
	</p>

</example>

<example xml:id="example-opt-singularity-no-extremes">
	<title>A singularity can preclude absolute extremes</title>

	<p>
	The function <m>q(t) = 1 / t</m> has no absolute minimum because
	<me> q \to -\infty \qquad\text{as}\qquad t \to t^- </me>.
	In particular,
	for every <m>t \lt 0</m>,
	we will always see <m>q(t/2) \lt q(t)</m>,
	so there is never any <em>lowest</em> <m>q</m>-value.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-opt-reciprocal-singularity">
		<caption>Singular behaviour can sometimes preclude absolute extremes.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-opt-reciprocal-singularity-no-min-max" width="55.5%">
			<description>Graph of the reciprocal function demonstrating that singular behaviour sometimes precludes absolute extremes.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="opt.d/reciprocal-singularity-no-min-max.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	With similar reasoning we can say that <m>q</m> has no absolute maximum on its domain because
	<me> q \to \infty \qquad\text{as}\qquad t \to t^+ </me>.
	</p>

</example>

<example xml:id="example-opt-bounded-domain-no-extremes">
	<title>A bounded function with no absolute extremes</title>

	<p>
	Consider the function <m>q(t) = \sqrt{t}</m> on the domain <m>0 \lt t \lt 1</m>.
	This function has <em>no</em> absolute minimum on this domain,
	because for every <m>t</m> you consider in the domain,
	you will find that <m>t/2</m> is also in the domain but the function achieves a lower value there:
	<me> \sqrt{t / 2} \lt \sqrt{t} \qquad\text{for every}\qquad 0 \lt t \lt 1 </me>.
	By similar reasoning near <m>t \approx 1</m>,
	there is no absolute maximum on this domain because you can always make <m>t</m> slightly closer to <m>1</m>
	(but still less than <m>1</m>)
	and the function value will be higher.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-opt-sqrt">
		<caption>Excluded domain endpoints sometimes preclude absolute extremes.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-opt-sqrt-no-min-max" width="40.2%">
			<description>Graph demonstrating that excluded domain endpoints sometimes preclude absolute extremes.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="opt.d/sqrt-no-min-max.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

</section>

<section>
<title>The Extreme Value Theorem</title>

<p>
We have seen that a function can fail to have an absolute extreme because of <term>unbounded behaviour</term>
(<xref ref="example-opt-changing-domains" /> and <xref ref="example-opt-singularity-no-extremes" />),
but also because of <term>endpoint behaviour</term>
(<xref ref="example-opt-bounded-domain-no-extremes" />).
If we take away those two possibilities,
then we are always guaranteed to have <em>both</em> an absolute maximum and minimum.
</p>

<definition>
	<title>Closed and bounded domains</title>
	<p><ol>
		<li> A domain is called <term>closed</term> if it contains its endpoints. </li>
		<li>
			A domain is called <term>bounded</term> if it can be entirely contained in some finite-length domain <m>-M \le t \le M</m>
			for some sufficiently large <m>M</m>.
		</li>
	</ol></p>
</definition>

<example>
	<title>Closed and bounded domains</title>
	<p><ol>

		<li>
			The initial domain <m>-1 \le t \le 2</m> from <xref ref="example-opt-changing-domains" /> is both closed and bounded.
			It is closed because it contains both endpoints <m>t = -1</m> and <m>t = 2</m>,
			and it is bounded because it fits inside <m>-2 \le t \le 2</m>.
			On the other hand, the expanded domain <m>t \ge -1</m> from <xref ref="example-opt-changing-domains" /> is no longer bounded,
			because it is unbounded on the right and will never fit inside a finite-length domain.
			However, it <em>is</em> still closed,
			because it contains its only endpoint <m>t = -1</m>.
		</li>

		<li>
			The domain <m>0 \lt t \lt 1</m> from <xref ref="example-opt-bounded-domain-no-extremes" /> is bounded but not closed.
			It is bounded because it fits inside <m>-1 \le t \le 1</m>,
			but it is not closed because it contains neither of its endpoints <m>t = 0</m> and <m>t = 1</m>.
		</li>

	</ol></p>
</example>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-opt-EVT">
	<title>Extreme Value Theorem</title>
	<p>
	A continuous function on a closed and bounded domain <m>a \le t \le b</m> <em>always</em> achieves <em>both</em> an absolute minimum and an absolute maximum value.
	</p>
</theorem>

<remark><p><ul>

	<li>
	The <xref ref="theorem-opt-EVT" text="title" /> doesn't tell you <em>where</em> or <em>at how many locations in that domain</em> that the absolute extremes will occur,
	it only tells you that they exist on that domain.
	</li>

	<li>
	Note that the converse is not necessarily true:
	if a function is not continuous,
	or if its domain is not closed or not bounded (or both),
	it <em>can still achieve</em> either or both of an absolute maximum and minimum on that domain.
	</li>

	<li>
	Our justification of the <xref ref="theorem-fund-thm-mean-value" text="title" />
	actually relies on the <xref ref="theorem-opt-EVT" text="title" /> <mdash />
	do you see how?
	</li>

</ul></p></remark>

<exercise>
	<title>Rechecking our examples</title>
	<p>
	Go back through the examples we have already considered in <xref ref="section-opt-abs-extremes" />,
	and determine which satisfy the <em>continuous</em> and <em>closed and bounded domain</em> hypotheses of the <xref ref="theorem-opt-EVT" text="title" />.
	</p>
</exercise>

<p> Here are a few more examples. </p>

<!-- THIS IS really just a repeat of the 1/t behaviour...
<example>
	<title>Unbounded behaviour on an unbounded domain</title>

	<p>
	The function <m>\ln(t)</m> has domain <m>t \gt 0</m>,
	which is both unbounded and not closed,
	so the <xref ref="theorem-opt-EVT" text="title" /> does not apply.
	And this function in fact has no absolute minimum because of the singularity as <m>t \to 0^+</m>,
	and no absolute maximum because of the unbounded long-term behaviour as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
	</p>

	TODO graph? or just xref to graph?

</example>
-->

<example xml:id="example-opt-long-term-no-extremes">
	<title>An unbounded, non-closed domain</title>

	<p>
	In <xref ref="example-opt-singularity-no-extremes" /> we considered
	the function <m>q(t) = 1 / t</m> on its full domain,
	and determined that there were no absolute extremes because of the singularity at <m>t = 0</m>.
	However, suppose we exclude this singularity by only considering the domain <m>t \gt 0</m>.
	This domain is both unbounded and not closed,
	so the <xref ref="theorem-opt-EVT" text="title" /> does not apply.
	And this function in fact has no absolute minimum because of the long-term behaviour as <m>t \to \infty</m>,
	because the function continually decreases without reaching a lowest value.
	It has hs no absolute maximum because of the excluded endpoint at <m>t = 1</m>,
	because there one can always take <m>t \approx 1^+</m> closer and closer,
	and the graph will inch higher without reaching a highest value.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-opt-reciprocal-long-term">
		<caption>Long-term behaviour on an unbounded domain can sometimes preclude absolute extremes.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-opt-reciprocal-long-term-no-min-max" width="53.8%">
			<description>Graph of the reciprocal function demonstrating that long-term behaviour sometimes precludes absolute extremes.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="opt.d/reciprocal-long-term-no-min-max.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<example>
	<title>Discontinuous behaviour on a closed, bounded domain</title>

	<p>
	The function <me> q(t) = \begin{cases} t \amp -1 \lt t \lt 1 \\ 0 \amp t = \pm 1 \end{cases} </me>
	has a closed and bounded domain <m>-1 \le t \le 1</m> but is discontinuous at its endpoints,
	so the <xref ref="theorem-opt-EVT" text="title" /> does not apply.
	And this function in fact has no absolute extremes because it is always possible to get a little closer to the endpoints and achieve a slightly higher or lower output than before.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-opt-discontinuous-no-min-max">
		<caption>Discontinuities sometimes preclude absolute extremes.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-opt-discontinuous-no-min-max" width="50.8%">
			<description>Graph of a discontinuous function demonstrating that discontinuities sometimes preclude absolute extremes.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="opt.d/discontinuous-no-min-max.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<example>
	<title>Extremes can still exist even when the theorem does not apply</title>

	<p>
	Consider the function
	<me> q(t) = \begin{cases} -t^2 \amp -1 \lt t \lt 0 \\ 1 - 2 t^2 \amp 0 \le t \le 1 \end{cases} </me>.
	This function is not continuous,
	and its domain <m>-1 \lt t \le 1</m> is bounded but not closed,
	since the endpoint <m>t = -1</m> is not included in the domain.
	Yet the function still achieves both an absolute minimum value <m>q(1) = -1</m>
	and an absolute maximum value <m>q(0) = 1</m>.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-opt-discontinuous-shifted-parabola">
		<caption>A discontinuous function can still have absolute extremes.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-opt-discontinuous-shifted-parabola" width="59.7%">
			<description>Graph of a broken parabola demonstrating that a discontinuous function can still have absolute extremes.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="opt.d/discontinuous-shifted-parabola.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

</section>

<section>
<title>Searching for extremes</title>

<p>
If <m>q(t^\ast)</m> is the greatest value on the entire domain being considered,
then it also needs to be the greatest value on any little <q>neighbourhood</q> of <m>t = t^\ast</m>.
In other words,
<em>an absolute maximum must also be a local maximum.</em>
And similarly for absolute minimums.
And we also know that local extremes must occur at <em>critical points</em>.
This leads to a simple strategy,
though we also need to take into account that extremes can occur at endpoints,
or not occur at all because of endpoint behaviour.
</p>

<algorithm xml:id="procedure-opt-abs-extremes">
	<title>Determining absolute extreme values and locations</title>
	<p><ul>

		<li>
			For a function that is continuous on a closed and bounded domain,
			make a list of the interior critical points.
			Add the endpoints to that list,
			and then evaluate the function at each point in the list.
			The greatest result is the absolute maximum and the least result is the absolute minimum.
		</li>

		<li>
			For a general function,
			break up the domain under consideration into domains of continuity.
			<em>On each subdomain</em>,
			determine the absolute extremes as above,
			but with special consideration of unbounded or non-closed endpoints to see if the outputs rise higher/lower than any previously found absolute extreme.
			The overall absolute extremes,
			if any,
			are then the greatest/least of the absolute extremes on each subdomain.
		</li>

	</ul>
	</p>
</algorithm>

<example>
	<title>Absolute extremes for a continuous function on a closed and bounded domain</title>

	<p>
	Consider the function <me> q(t) = t^2 (4 - t)^2 \qquad 1 \le t \le 5 </me>.
	This is a polynomial so it is continuous,
	and the stated domain is both closed and bounded.
	</p>

	<p> To determine the critical points, we need the derivative function. </p>

	<sage>
		<input>
			var('t')
			q(t) = t^2 * (4 - t)^2
			q.derivative().factor()
		</input>
		<output>
			t |--> 4*(t - 2)*(t - 4)*t
		</output>
	</sage>

	<p>
	From the factored form of the derivative,
	<me> q'(t) = 4 t (t - 2) (t - 4) </me>,
	we see that the critical points are <m>t = 0, 2, 4</m>.
	However, <m>t = 0</m> is outside of our stated domain,
	so we discard it.
	So our full list of critical points and endpoints is
	<me> t = 1, 2, 4, 5 </me>.
	Now we evaluate:
	<md>
		<mrow>
			q(1) \amp = 9 \amp
			q(2) \amp = 16 \amp
			q(4) \amp = 0 \amp
			q(5) \amp = 25
		</mrow>
	</md>.
	So the absolute minimum of <m>q(4) = 0</m> occurs at the interior critical point <m>t = 4</m>,
	(and so this must also be a local minimum).
	The absolute maximum of <m>q(5) = 25</m> occurs at an endpoint.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-opt-poly-min-max">
		<caption>Graph of <m>q(t)</m> and its extreme values.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-opt-w" width="51.1%">
			<description>Graph of the polynomial function analyzed in this example, with its absolute extremes marked.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="opt.d/w.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<example>
	<title>Absolute extremes for a discontinuous function</title>

	<p>
	Consider the function
	<me>
		q(t) =
		\begin{cases}
			t^2 \amp -1 \le t \lt 2 \\
			t - 3 \amp 2 \le t \le 8 \\
			- \frac{1}{t - 8} \amp t \gt 8
		\end{cases}
	</me>.
	The stated subdomains already split this function up into domains of continuity for us.
	</p>

	<case>
		<title>On <m>-1 \le t \lt 2</m></title>
		<p>
		On this domain we have <m>q'(t) = 2 t</m>,
		so there is a critical point at <m>t = 0</m>.
		We evaluate <md><mrow> q(-1) \amp = 1 \amp q(0) = 0 </mrow></md>.
		We also note that near the excluded endpoint <m>t = 2</m>,
		the graph rises to <m>q(t) \approx 4</m>.
		So while <m>q(0) = 0</m> is the absolute minimum on this subdomain,
		there is no absolute maximum here.
		</p>
	</case>

	<case>
		<title>On <m>2 \le t \le 8</m></title>
		On this domain,
		the derivative is <m>q'(t) = 1</m> and so there are no critical points.
		In fact, the graph here is just a line with positive slope,
		so we know that it rises from an absolute minimum <m>q(2) = -1</m> at the left endpoint
		to an absolute maximum <m>q(8) = 5</m> at the right endpoint.
	</case>

	<case>
		<title>On <m>t \gt 8</m></title>
		<p>
		On this domain the derivative is <me> q'(t) = \frac{1}{(t - 8)^2} </me>,
		so again there are no critical points.
		At the excluded endpoint <m>t = 8</m> the function actually has a singularity,
		with <me> q \to - \infty \qquad\text{as}\qquad t \to 8^+ </me>.
		In fact, not only does this tell us that the function cannot have an absolute minimum on this domain,
		it tells us that <alert>the function cannot have an overall absolute minimum</alert>.
		We should also investigate the unbounded endpoint by considering long-term behaviour:
		<me>  q \to 0 \qquad\text{as}\qquad t \to \infty </me>.
		Now, the derivative is positive on this subdomain,
		so we can say that the graph is increasing up from the singularity at <m>t = 8</m> to the approach the horizontal asymptote at <m>q = 0</m> from below.
		So there is also no absolute maximum on this domain.
		</p>
	</case>

	<p>
	Finally, we combine our findings.
	<ul>

		<li><p>
			We had highs of
			<md>
				<mrow> q(t) \amp \approx 4 \amp q(8) \amp = 5 \amp q(t) \amp \approx 0 </mrow>
				<mrow> \text{for } t \amp \approx 2^- \amp \amp \amp \text{for } t \amp \gt\gt 8 </mrow>
			</md>.
			So we can say <m>q(8) = 5</m> is the overall absolute maximum.
		</p></li>

		<li><p>
			We had lows of
			<md>
				<mrow> q(0) \amp = 0 \amp q(2) \amp = -1 \amp q(t) \amp \lt\lt -1  </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp \amp \amp \amp \text{for } t \amp \approx 8^+ </mrow>
			</md>.
			If it were not for the singularity at <m>t = 8</m>,
			we would have <m>q(2) = -1</m> as the overall absolute minimum,
			but because the singularity sinks lower and lower for <m>t \approx 8^+</m>,
			the function does not have an absolute minimum.
		</p></li>

	</ul>
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-opt-procedure">
		<caption>Results of analyzing absolute extremes of a discontinuous function.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-opt-abs-extreme-procedure-discont" width="85.5%">
			<description>Graph illustrating results of analyzing absolute extremes of a discontinuous function.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="opt.d/abs-extreme-procedure-discont.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

</section>

<section>
<title>The Second Derivative Test</title>

<p>
Often we searching for only one particular type of absolute extreme:
<em>maximize profit</em> or <em>minimize energy use</em>.
In this case,
it's useful to be able to quickly classify critical points
without having to determine domains of increase and decrease
in order to use the <xref ref="pattern-curves-first-derivative-test" text="title" />.
Since critical points that are not cusps must be rounded peaks or valleys,
the concavity can tell us whether we are at a local maximum or a local minimum.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-opt-second-derivative-test">
	<title>Second Derivative Test</title>

	<p>
	Suppose that <m>q</m> is a twice-differentiable function
	and has a critical point at <m>t = t^\ast</m> with <m>q'(t^\ast) = 0</m>.
	<ol>

		<li>
			If <m>q''(t^\ast)</m> is positive,
			then <m>q</m> must be concave up near that point and so has a <em>local minimum</em> there.
		</li>

		<li>
			If <m>q''(t^\ast)</m> is negative,
			then <m>q</m> must be concave down near that point and so has a <em>local maximum</em> there.
		</li>

		<li>
			If <m>q''(t^\ast)</m> is zero,
			then <alert>no conclusion can be made</alert>.
			Use the <xref ref="pattern-curves-first-derivative-test" text="title" /> instead to classify the critical point.
		</li>

	</ol>
	</p>

</identity>

<figure xml:id="figure-opt-second-deriv">
	<caption>Graphical representation of the Second Derivative Test.</caption>

	<sidebyside valign="top" widths="35.2% 35.2%">

		<figure>
			<caption>A local minimum at the valley of a concave-up portion of the graph.</caption>
			<image xml:id="image-opt-2nd-deriv-test-2">
				<description>A graph illustrating a local minimum at the valley of a concave-up portion of the graph.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="opt.d/2nd-deriv-test-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<figure>
			<caption>A local maximum at the peak of a concave-down portion of the graph.</caption>
			<image xml:id="image-opt-2nd-deriv-test-1">
				<description>A graph illustrating a local maximum at the peak of a concave-down portion of the graph.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="opt.d/2nd-deriv-test-1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

	</sidebyside>

</figure>

<warning><p>
	Watch out for the reversal of sign to extreme type in the test:
	<alert>positive means minimum</alert> and <alert>negative means maximum</alert>.
	To not get mixed up,
	it's better to first go through the thought process of
	<em>positive means concave up, and concave up means minimum</em>,
	and similarly for a negative second derivative value.
</p></warning>

<example>
	<title>Applying the Second Derivative Test</title>

	<p>
	Let's revisit
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow> A(t) = \ccmint{0}{t}{ (u - 2) (u - 4)^2 }{u} </mrow>
		<mrow> A'(t) = (t - 2) (t - 4)^2 </mrow>
	</md>
	from <xref ref="example-curves-1st-deriv-test-for-accumulation" />,
	where we previously applied the <xref ref="pattern-curves-first-derivative-test" text="title" />.
	This time will apply the <xref ref="pattern-opt-second-derivative-test" text="title" /> to verify our previous classifications of the critical points <m>t = 2, 4</m>.
	</p>

	<sage>
		<input>
			var('t')
			qp(t) = (t - 2) * (t - 4)^2
			qp.derivative().factor()
		</input>
		<output>
			t |--> (3*t - 8)*(t - 4)
		</output>
	</sage>

	<p>
	We have chosen to have Sage return the second derivative <me> A''(t) = (3 t - 8) (t - 4) </me>
	in factored form not because we are looking for inflection points,
	but just so that it is easier to determine whether <m>q''(t)</m> is positive or negative at specific points.
	For example, at the critical point <m>t = 2</m>,
	we have
	<md><mrow> 3 t - 8 \amp \lt 0 \amp t - 4 \amp \lt 0 </mrow></md>
	so <m>A''(2) \gt 0</m>.
	Since this means that the graph of <m>A(t)</m> must be concave up near <m>t = 2</m>,
	that critical point must be a local minimum,
	which agrees with our previous conclusion from the First Derivative Test.
	On the other hand,
	clearly <m>A''(4) = 0</m>,
	so the <xref ref="pattern-opt-second-derivative-test" text="title" /> does not tell us anything about this critical point,
	and we would have to fall back on our previous analysis using the First Derivative Test.
	</p>

</example>

</section>

<section>
<title>Optimization problems</title>

<p>
Finally,
we'll consider some applied examples of minimizing or maximizing a particular quantity,
and provide an overall strategy.
</p>

<example>
	<title>Minimizing area</title>

	<statement><p>
		The owners of a property wish to fence off a rectangular area of land bordering a straight stretch of river.
		They have
		<quantity><mag>2400</mag><unit base="foot" /></quantity>
		of fencing.
		No fence is required along the river,
		which will act as a natural boundary on one side of the rectangular area.
		How large of an area can they enclose?
		What dimensions will it be?
	</p></statement>

	<solution>

		<p>
		Let <m>x</m> represent the <q>width</q> of the rectangular area parallel to the river,
		and let <m>y</m> represent how far away from the river the area will stretch.
		</p>

		<figure>
			<caption>A rectangular region, fenced on three sides and bordered by a river on the fourth side.</caption>
			<image xml:id="image-opt-fence" width="59.1%">
				<description>Diagram of a rectangular region, fenced on three sides and bordered by a river on the fourth side.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="opt.d/fence.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p>
		We would like to maximize the area <m>A = x y</m>.
		To enclose the largest possible area,
		we should use all of the fence available,
		but we can't use more than that.
		So we are constrained by requirement that the portion of the perimeter that is to be fenced should be equal to the available amount of fencing:
		<me> x + 2 y = 2400 </me>.
		Isolating <m>x</m>,
		we can use this constraint to re-express the area as a function of <m>y</m>: <me> A(y) = (2400 - 2 y) y = 2400 y - 2 y^2 </me>.
		The domain we are concerned with is <me> 0 \lt y \lt 1200 </me>,
		where at one extreme of <m>y = 0</m> we would have arranged all of the fence in a line parallel to the river,
		enclosing no area,
		and at the other extreme of <m>y = 1200</m> we would have arranged two lines of fence
		<quantity><mag>1200</mag><unit base="foot" /></quantity> long right next to each other,
		perpendicular to the river, and again enclosing no area.
		Since our area function is a concave down parabola with <me> A(0) = A(1200) = 0 </me>,
		by symmetry we can probably guess that the peak of the parabola will occur at <m>y = 600</m>,
		but let's confirm.
		</p>

		<p>
		The derivative is
		<me> A'(y) = 2400 - 4 y = 4 (600 - y) </me>,
		so we indeed have a critical point at <m>y = 600</m>.
		We also have <me> A''(y) = -4 </me>,
		so the function's graph is always concave down
		(as we knew),
		and so there is a local maximum at <m>y = 600</m>.
		We have already investigated the endpoint behaviour and found <m>0</m> enclosed area at those extremes,
		so <me> A(600) = 720000 </me> is the absolute maximum.
		This means that a maximum area of
		<quantity><mag>72000</mag><unit base="foot" exp="2" /></quantity>,
		running <quantity><mag>1200</mag><unit base="foot" /></quantity> along the river,
		and extending <quantity><mag>600</mag><unit base="foot" /></quantity> away from the river.
		</p>

	</solution>

</example>

<algorithm xml:id="procedure-opt">
	<title>Solving an optimization problem</title>
	<p><ol>
		<li>
			Draw a diagram, if appropriate.
			Assign variables to the unknown parameters.
			Express the quantity to be optimized in terms of those variables.
		</li>
		<li>
			Identify any constraints.
			Use the constraints to reduce the expression for the quantity to be optimized to a single variable.
		</li>
		<li>
			Identify a reasonable domain for the function,
			and then carry out <xref ref="procedure-opt-abs-extremes" /> on that domain.
		</li>
		<li>
			As an extra check,
			you can use the <xref ref="pattern-opt-second-derivative-test" text="title" /> to ensure that you have properly identified a minimum or maximum,
			whichever was sought.
		</li>
	</ol></p>
</algorithm>

<example>
	<title>Minimizing material</title>

	<statement><p>
		A manufacturer wishes to design a cylindrical can to hold
		<quantity><mag>1</mag><unit base="liter" /></quantity>
		of vegetable oil.
		Assuming the sides and ends of the can are made of the same material and same thickness of material,
		what dimensions should the can be to minimize the amount of material used for one can?
	</p></statement>

	<solution>

		<p>
		Let's carry out <xref ref="procedure-opt" />.
		<ol>

			<li>

				<p>
				Let <m>h</m> represent the height and <m>R</m> the radius of the cylindrical can,
				measured in centimetres.
				Since the material is all the same thickness,
				we can use the exterior surface area of the can to measure how much material has been used.
				If we cut off the ends of the cylinder,
				and then slice it down the side and unroll it,
				we have two circles and a rectangle,
				where the height of the original cylinder is one side length of the rectangle and the circumference of the circular ends is the other side length.
				</p>

				<figure>
					<caption>Surface area of a cylindrical can, in pieces.</caption>
					<image xml:id="image-opt-can" width="83.5%">
						<description>A diagram illustrating the surface area of a cylindrical can, in pieces.</description>
						<latex-image><xi:include href="opt.d/can.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
					</image>
				</figure>

				<p>
				So the surface area is
				<me> A = 2 \pi R^2 + 2 \pi R h </me>.
				We would like to minimize this quantity.
				</p>

			</li>

			<li>
				Our constraint is that the volume needs to be
				<quantity><mag>1</mag><unit base="liter" /></quantity>.
				The volume of a cylinder is <me> V = \pi R^2 h </me>.
				(Notice that this formula is the result of <q>adding up</q> the constant cross-sectional area <m>\pi R^2</m>,
				<m>h</m> times.)
				But we need to make sure our units are in accord,
				so let's take our constraint as a volume of
				<quantity><mag>1000</mag><unit base="meter" prefix="centi" exp="3" /></quantity>.
				Isolating <m>h</m> in the equation <m>V = 1000</m>,
				we have <me> h = \frac{1000}{\pi R^2} </me>,
				and so our area formula becomes
				<me> A(R) = 2 \pi R^2 + 2 \pi R \cdot \frac{1000}{\pi R^2} = 2 \pi R^2 + \frac{2000}{R} </me>.
			</li>

			<li>

				<p>
				In mathematical terms,
				the radius can be as small as you like or as large as you like,
				as long as it is positive.
				If the radius were very small then the height would need to be large in order to meet the
				<quantity><mag>1</mag><unit base="liter" /></quantity>
				constraint,
				and likewise if the radius were very large the height would need to be very small.
				So, in practical terms,
				a very small or very large radius would be undesirable because it would be difficult to ship and store such cans.
				But for now, let's take the domain to be <m>R \gt 0</m>.
				</p>

				<p>
				We have <me> A'(R) = 4 \pi R - \frac{2000}{R^2} </me>.
				This derivative is undefined at <m>R = 0</m>,
				but that is not in our domain.
				So let's look for critical points of the <m>A'(R) = 0</m> variety.
				<md alignment="gather">
					<mrow> 4 \pi R - \frac{2000}{R^2} = 0 </mrow>
					<mrow> \pi R^3 - 500 = 0 </mrow>
					<mrow> R = \sqrt[3]{\frac{500}{\pi}} </mrow>
				</md>
				</p>

				<p>
				Since our domain is both unbounded and not closed,
				we need to investigate the endpoint behaviour.
				Our domain does not include the endpoint <m>R = 0</m>,
				but for <m>R \approx 0^+</m>,
				in <me> A(R) = 2 \pi R^2 + \frac{2000}{R} </me>
				the first term is also close to zero but the second term is large and positive.
				So we can say <me> A \to \infty \qquad\text{as}\qquad R \to 0^+ </me>.
				Our domain is also unbounded to the right,
				so we should check the long-term behaviour.
				For <m>R \to \infty</m>,
				the first term in our expression for <m>A</m> is now large and positive,
				while the second term is close to zero.
				So we can also say <me> A \to \infty \qquad\text{as}\qquad R \to \infty </me>.
				Since we only found one interior critical point,
				the fact that <m>A</m> gets large on either side of this critical point let us conclude that <m>A</m> must hit its absolute minimum there.
				</p>

			</li>

			<li>
				We also have <me> A''(R) = 4 \pi + \frac{4000}{R^3} </me>,
				which is positive on our entire domain.
				So the graph of <m>A(R)</m> is always concave up on our domain,
				which corroborates our conclusion that our critical point is a minimum.
			</li>

		</ol>
		</p>

		<p>
		Finally,
		we complete our solution by making sure we answer the question posed.
		We have one dimension that minimizes the can's area,
		the radius,
		but we should also calculate the corresponding height.
		We have
		<me> R = \sqrt[3]{\frac{500}{\pi}} \approx 5.42 \; \mathrm{cm} </me>
		<md>
			<mrow> h \amp = \frac{1000}{\pi R^2} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \frac{1000}{\pi {(500/\pi)}^{2/3}} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = 2 \sqrt[3]{\frac{500}{\pi}} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \approx 10.84 \; \mathrm{cm} </mrow>
		</md>.
		So it turns out that the minimum area that meets the volume constraint occurs when the height is equal to the diameter.
		</p>
	</solution>

</example>

<!-- TODO shortest distance ? -->

</section>

